Implementing a recursive retry utility is an absolute classic senior engineer interview question. It directly tests your ability to orchestrate structural microtask flow purely through explicit .then() and .catch() chains.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Why do we need…?
In production software engineering, the retry pattern is an absolute requirement for handling flaky operations—situations where an action fails temporarily but is highly likely to succeed if you simply try again a moment later.
Here are the four most common real-world use cases where you will write or use this exact utility.
1. Handling Unstable Network Requests (Microservices & APIs)
When your frontend app or backend microservice talks to an external API (like a payment gateway or weather service), connections can drop for a fraction of a second due to packet loss or brief Wi-Fi drops.

• The Problem: A user clicks “Buy Now,” and a temporary 503 Network Error occurs. If you don’t retry, the user sees a red error screen and leaves.

• The Retry Fix: The app silently retries the payment API 2 more times in the background. The second attempt succeeds, and the user experiences a smooth checkout without ever knowing a network blip happened.
2. Bypassing API Rate Limiting (Throttling)
Public APIs (like Twitter, GitHub, or OpenAI) enforce rate limits. If you send too many requests at once, they will reject your request with a 429 Too Many Requests status code.

• The Problem: Your app is scraping data or loading a dashboard, and hits a temporary block.

• The Retry Fix: Instead of crashing, your function catches the 429 error, waits briefly, and retries. (In production, this is combined with Exponential Backoff, meaning you wait longer between each retry — e.g., 1s, then 2s, then 4s).
3. Database Connection Lifecycles
When a backend server boots up or handles thousands of simultaneous users, the connection pool to the database (like PostgreSQL or MongoDB) can briefly saturate or time out.

• The Problem: A user requests a profile page, but the server fails to query the database on the exact millisecond the pool is resetting.

• The Retry Fix: The backend retries the query function up to 3 times before giving up and throwing a “Server Error” page.
4. File System Operations & Lockouts
In Node.js applications, when multiple processes are reading, writing, or appending to the exact same log file or configuration file, the operating system will temporarily lock the file.

• The Problem: Process A tries to modify config.json while Process B is reading it, resulting in an EBUSY: resource busy or locked system exception.

• The Retry Fix: Process A catches the lock error, retries a few milliseconds later when Process B is finished, and completes the write operation cleanly.
Summary Architectural Rule…
The golden rule of systems engineering is: Never retry a deterministic error, only retry transient errors.

• ❌ Do NOT retry: A 404 Not Found or 401 Unauthorized error. If a file doesn't exist or a password is wrong, retrying 100 times will never change the outcome.

• ✅ DO retry: A 503 Service Unavailable, 504 Gateway Timeout, or network disconnect. These are environmental failures that fix themselves over time.
The Complete Implementation…
// Implement Retry Promisefunction retry(fetchData, retries) {
console.log("Checking the params what is comming", retries);
// Return a new promise so the caller can use .then() and .catch() methods
return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
// Define an internal recursive helper function to handle the attemts
function attempt(remainingRetries) {
fetchData()
.then((result) => {
// Stop immediately after success
resolve(result);
})
.catch((error) => {
if (remainingRetries > 0) {
console.log(
`Attempt failed. Retrying... (${remainingRetries} left)`,
);
// Recursive async flow - execute the next attempt
attempt(remainingRetries - 1);
} else {
// Reject after all retries fail
reject(`All retries exhausted. Final Error: ${error}`);
}
});
}
// Trigger the initial first attempt (passing the initial retry count)
attempt(retries);
});
}
// Mock API utility that fails twice before succeeding on the third try
let callCount = 0;
const unstableMockAPI = () => {
return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
callCount++;
if (callCount < 2) {
reject(`Network Timeout (Call #${callCount})`);
} else {
resolve(`Successfully loaded secure data! (Call #${callCount})`);
}
});
};
// Execute the test configuration
console.log("Starting network operations...");
retry(unstableMockAPI, 2)
.then((data) => console.log("SUCCESS TARGET:", data))
.catch((err) => console.error("FAILURE TARGET:", err));
Step-by-Step Simulation (How It Executes)…
Let’s assume you configure retries = 2. This gives the system a total of 3 execution attempts (the initial call + 2 fallback retries).

• Initial Invocation: retry() initializes the structural layout and triggers attempt(2).

• Attempt 1 (Fails): fetchData() returns a rejected promise. The runtime bypasses .then() and falls straight into .catch(). The conditional guard confirms 2 > 0, decrements the loop depth counter, and invokes attempt(1).

• Attempt 2 (Fails): fetchData() rejects again. The .catch() block verifies 1 > 0 and triggers the final recursive baseline jump: attempt(0).

• Attempt 3 (Fails): fetchData() rejects for a third time. The conditional guard 0 > 0 evaluates to false. The stack stops processing recursive functions and fires the master reject() callback, terminating the operation gracefully.
Deep Dive into the Tested Concepts…
Closures & State Persistence
The internal nested function attempt() creates a closure over the environment variables of retry(). This is exactly how attempt() retains access to the master resolve and reject tokens across multiple separate execution ticks of the Event Loop without polluting global memory.
